SA2B here!  So, I'm thinkin' about becoming a social worker, y'know, helpin' out the little guys who got it rough. Kids who've been through the wringer, families messin' up, that kinda thing.  I figure, I can offer a few things to the social work game. First off, I'm all about helpin' people, always have been. Secondly, I treat everyone with respect, no matter what. And, I'm a straight-shooter, always doin' the right thing. I wanna make things better for folks, not just in their lives, but for myself too. Gotta keep learnin' and growin' to be the best I can be.

See, I always wanted to do somethin' to make a difference, but wasn't sure how.  Went through high school and college, saw a lot of folks runnin' from their problems, makin' bad choices.  That's why I got my psychology degree, figured it would give me some tools to help.

Then one day, this friend of mine had this kid, just sixteen, all nervous, stayin' on her couch. Turns out, he was runnin' from some messed-up parents. Next day, heard he'd called the cops. Figured I'd lend a hand, so I went over to his folks' place. Talked to the cops, told 'em about my degree and my concerns. They wanted me to talk to the parents, said there wasn't much they could do.

Well, when I talked to the parents, they were all jumpy, makin' excuses for how their son was just "manipulative" for gettin' the cops involved. It was a "simple" family fight, they said.  That's when it hit me, that's what I wanna do, help these kids who are stuck in these messed-up situations. 

Social work ain't just about helpin' kids, though. It's about standin' up for what's right, fightin' for those who can't fight for themselves. You know, like when folks say everyone's an individual, but then they wanna make everyone fit in the same mold? That ain't right. I'm unique, and I wanna see everyone else be unique too.

Back in high school and college, I did my part. Dyed my hair crazy colors, wore what I wanted, pierced my ears, joined the GSBA, spoke up against racism and discrimination whenever I saw it.  That's what social justice is all about, standin' up for what's right, even when it's hard. And I'm gonna keep doin' it.

Alright, lemme tell ya about this thing called insomnia, see? Some folks think it's all in your genes or your body, kinda like a bug in the system. They call that the "biological" model. Others say it's more about where you're from, who your folks are, and the whole shebang of life's craziness. That's the "sociocultural" model.

So, to figure this thing out, we gotta look at both sides. Like, some folks have trouble falling asleep or staying asleep (that's insomnia, plain and simple). Others sleep way too much, or fall asleep at random times (that's the hypersomnia crew). Then there's folks who have crazy dreams, sleepwalk, or even talk in their sleep. It's a real mixed bag!

Now, the "biological" folks say it's all about these tiny things in your brain called neurons. They fire and they don't fire, and that's what makes you sleep or wake up.  This one study used mice, see, and they found these special neurons that control sleep. When these neurons get messed up, bam! You've got trouble sleeping. 

The "sociocultural" folks say it's more about your environment. Where you live, who you hang out with, even your job can affect your sleep. It's like this big web of stuff that all works together.

Hey there! So, let's talk about this thing called Central Auditory Processing Disorder, or CAPD for short.  It's kinda like, your brain has trouble understanding what your ears are hearing, even if you can hear just fine. Imagine trying to sort out a bunch of noisy voices in a crowded room – that's what it's like for folks with CAPD. 

This wasn't always called CAPD, though. Back in the 50s, they called it "auditory imperception."  A bunch of smart folks started figuring out how it works, like these researchers in Italy and a guy named Kimura. They came up with tests to see if a kid's brain was processing sounds the way it should.  

CAPD can show up in all sorts of ways.  Maybe someone has trouble hearing sounds from different directions, or they can't tell the difference between similar sounds, like "cat" and "hat." They might also have a hard time understanding speech when there's a lot of background noise, or they might not pick up on changes in tone, like when someone's being sarcastic.  It's like their brain is missing some of the clues!

So, how do you know if someone has CAPD? Well, there are these special tests that audiologists and speech therapists give. They might ask you to listen to different sounds and tell them what you hear, or they might watch how you respond to different kinds of auditory information.  There's no one magic test, though, and we don't know exactly what causes CAPD.

So, this play, Twelfth Night, it's kinda saying that while pretending to be someone else can work for a while, like, REALLY work, you gotta ditch the fake eventually or you'll lose yourself, ya know?  The problem is, dropping the act can mess things up with your peeps. Some folks won't care, but others, they'll be ticked off about the whole charade.  It's like, do you keep up the lie to protect yourself, or do you risk hurting the people you care about? Tough choice, right?

This whole disguise thing gets even weirder when it comes to switching genders, like Viola did. Why'd she do it? Safety, I guess.  She's new in town, and playing a dude seems safer than being all vulnerable as a girl. It worked, but now she's cut off from other women, which is a bummer.  And get this, she's so convincing as a dude that Olivia, this chick, falls head over heels for her! Talk about awkward. Then there's Orsino, who's totally smitten with Viola but thinks she's a dude. It's a whole mess of feelings!

Twelfth Night makes you think, though. Maybe all this pretending helps people figure out what they REALLY feel. Like, is Olivia into guys or gals? Or maybe  Orsino's just confused about his own feelings? Viola's disguise kinda forces them to deal with stuff they've been ignoring.

But here's the kicker: Olivia's kinda quick to move on from Viola/Cesario to Sebastian, her twin bro. She seems more interested in looks than anything else.  Maybe she's just playing the game, ya know, like everyone else in this crazy play.

Alright, so lemme tell ya about this German place they called a "colony," right?  It was a real mess, especially in this place called South West Africa, now Namibia.  They were real meanies to the locals, like the Ovaherero and Nama folks,  kinda like a really bad bully. But hey, not all Germans were bad, ya know? Some were actually kinda cool.  Like in East Africa, they built schools and stuff for the local folks.  But in South West Africa, it was like, "nah, we ain't doin' that." They left it all up to these church groups, and they didn't give 'em much dough.  They did spend a ton of money on schools for the white folks though. Weird, right?  

Anyway, this messed up the whole place, even after the Germans were gone.  East Africa had lots of smart folks, but in South West Africa, most people couldn't read or write.   There are these books about this stuff, written way back when, mostly in German.  They just kinda describe what was goin' on.  Later, some folks wrote more books in English, comparing all the different colonies. They figured out that South West Africa was different 'cause there were a lot more white folks livin' there.   One guy, Cohen, wrote a whole thing about this, sayin' it all comes down to how many white folks were there.   It was mostly hot and dry, but still, a bunch of white folks settled there. By 1913, there were almost 15,000 of them, way more than in any other colony.

Man, music's gotten wild over the last hundred years, right? Like, there are so many different types now it's hard to keep track. You got your rap, your rock, your country, your jazz, your folk...  Heck, even those have tons of little branches and branches of branches!  But seriously, heavy metal rocks, dude! It's been around for about forty years and it's gone from just one sound to, like, a whole universe of sounds. It's all about feeling something deep, you know? It's like the music gets right in your soul, even if it's the dark side of your soul.

And the crazy part? People have been messing with metal since day one,  always trying to make it weirder and wilder. It's like a chain reaction, man!  One band does something new, and then a bunch of other bands are like, "Whoa, that's cool, let's take it even further!" And that's how we got all these crazy sub-genres, and sub-sub-genres, and who knows what else.  

Now, it's so hard to say what metal *is* anymore. It's like a melting pot of everything. But it all started somewhere, right? To get the whole picture, we gotta look back at what metal is really about.

It's more than just a bunch of loud music. It's a whole movement, a whole attitude. It's like a scream into the darkness. You got the heavy bass, the crushing volume, the wild energy, the crazy shows... It's like metal bands are saying, "We're not messing around, we're here to make you FEEL something!" And they're not afraid to get intense, man. They really know their instruments, and they're not afraid to show off.

And let's not forget about the drugs, dude. Back in the 70s, everyone was tripping out on all sorts of stuff, and it totally influenced the music.  Metal became a way to express that wild, chaotic energy.  It was like, "Hey, we're not afraid of the dark side, we embrace it!"

And you know what? It's still going strong today. Metal bands are still pushing boundaries, still exploring the darkest corners of the human experience. It's a pretty amazing thing, when you think about it.

Okay, so check this out. This dude, Henri Rousseau, painted like crazy back in the day, way before all those other weirdos were painting their weird dreams.  He's like, a Post-Impressionist, you know, one of those guys who did his own thing.  He had this painting, *The Dream*,  it's from 1910, and it's about this girl totally blown away by this crazy dreamland. But get this, it's also about Rousseau's own dreams, like, what he wanted to be and all that jazz. 

See, this dude dreamed of being a big shot artist, like, everyone loving his stuff and all that. But here's the catch:  he had this major inner struggle.  Should he paint like everyone else to get famous, or should he just do his own thing and be unique? *The Dream* is like his whole life story, y'know?

Rousseau, this guy, he was born way back in 1844, in France. His dad was a business kinda guy, and Rousseau, he didn't go to art school or nothin'. He was working for the government, like collecting tolls or somethin'. He even had this nickname, "douanier," which is like a customs inspector.  Life wasn't easy for him. He lost his first wife and a bunch of kids.  So, he decided to paint, to make himself feel better, I guess. 

He really wanted to be accepted by the art world, which is understandable, right?  He wasn't a fancy art school guy, he started painting later in life, and there were tons of other crazy talented artists around.  He even started getting noticed around the same time as Matisse, who was already a superstar. This guy Gordon wrote a book about French painters, and he says that Matisse was all about avoiding boring art, while Rousseau just wanted to paint something so "normal" that people would finally like him.

So, get this, right? A bunch of brainy folks have been saying that ethics and art, truth and beauty, are like, totally connected. And you know what? I kinda agree. Like, Keats, that poet dude, he said, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty - That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know."  We learn stuff through school and stuff, but  ethics and art, they just kinda...click with us, ya know? It's not like we're taught to appreciate a good painting or a good deed, it just happens. 

Think about it. We try to explain why something's art or why something's right, but can we really?  Like, we can talk about the Mona Lisa's colors and stuff, but that doesn't explain why it's so darn cool.  It's like when someone asks about your favorite book or song, you just kinda go, "There's just something about it..."  Art and morals, they're more than just rules or explanations, ya know? They're kinda like...transcendent, like there's this extra something special they got.  

Flannery O'Connor, she said stories are like, the only way to say some things, 'cause words just can't do it justice. Same with art and morals, there's this thing they got that goes beyond what you can put into words.

See, it's like we feel art and morals deep down, in this way that's hard to explain.  It's like, beyond our normal thinking, ya know? And literature, man, it's extra special 'cause it deals with values, with what's important in life. It's like life itself, full of stuff we gotta figure out.

So, yeah, I think art and morals are super connected 'cause they both hit us in this deep, meaningful way that words can't always capture.

Hey, check this out! Germany today is a total powerhouse, a country with its own awesome vibe, from the mountains near Munich to the Baltic Sea in Kiel. It's like one big party, all the way from Cologne on the Rhine River to Dresden by the Elbe. With a culture so unique, it makes sense that Germany, as we know it, came from all sorts of different groups and tribes. 

The place where it all started is called Germania, the homeland of the Germans. Where the name came from, though, is a mystery! Some say it's from a tribe called the Tungrians, who were like, "Yo, we're the Germans now!" before they crossed the Rhine and messed with the Gauls (according to Tacitus, a guy who wrote stuff a long time ago).  Julius Caesar, the guy who fought the Gauls and wrote about it, was the first to use the word "Germanus" to talk about these tough guys. He used it to tell the difference between the Gauls he beat and the Germans he hadn't conquered yet. Some think it came from a word the Gauls used for "neighbor," but who knows for sure? Caesar said in his book about the Gallic Wars that the Germans were always fighting the Gauls, like it was their daily routine (Caesar, 50-40 BC). Others think it comes from the spear the Germans used, called a "ger," or maybe from an old Irish word "garim," meaning "to shout," because Germans are loud, you know?

This Roman dude named Tacitus, who wrote stuff way back in AD 98, said the Germans were pure and hadn't mixed with other people, like they just appeared out of nowhere. He's like, "Why would anyone leave Asia or Africa for a place like Germany? It's wild, the weather is bad, and the people are grumpy!" (Tacitus, 98)

The Romans didn't really want to live in Germania, but they did send folks there to get stuff and fight sometimes. They mostly stayed in their own big empire. Meanwhile, the Germans hung out on the edge of Rome's territory, trading their stuff and even joining the Roman army (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17).

So there I was, staring down at this thing, my brain just kind of...spinning. I wasn't really *feeling* anything, just kinda watching it like a scientist, you know?  Thoughts were popping up and disappearing faster than I could catch them. It was like my brain was on autopilot, just soaking up the sight in front of me.

Remember that art book I got, the one about drawing with your "right brain"?  "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain" or something like that.  It taught you how to actually *see* things, like breaking down a whole scene, a kitchen with a fruit bowl and everything, into just that bowl of fruit.  That's what I was trying to do here, but my brain was overloaded.

I mean, Picasso had his blue period, Monet loved painting his gardens, and all those Renaissance guys were all about the colors. I was thinking, maybe this is my thing, my "Work in Brown."  My masterpiece.

I grabbed my weapon of choice - a mop - and got ready to create. My hand was steady, my mind focused. I could almost feel the artistic energy flowing through me.  The water swirled, so smooth and clear...then I whacked the toilet handle, and that's when it hit me.  This wasn't a masterpiece, it was a pile of brown mush someone left as a message for the poor schmuck who had to clean it. 

I flushed again, took a deep breath, and tried to focus.  I wrapped the toilet paper around my hand like a glove, ready to face the brown beast.  Why did people do this to others? It was like they were saying, "Hey, enjoy your day! Here's a little gift!"  A gift of poop.

Yo, check it! Teenagers are gettin' themselves killed behind the wheel, man. It's a real bummer.  

See, the thing is, their brains ain't fully cooked yet for all the craziness of driving. And, let's face it, they're newbies at this whole driving thing.  They crash more, spin out, speed like maniacs, and even go off the road more often.

And guess what? They're more likely to crash when they're cruisin' with their buddies – which, you know, is like, totally normal for teens. Some smart folks in California did a study and found the younger the passenger, the more likely they were to get into a fender bender.

So, states like California have tried to make things safer by giving teenagers these temporary licenses that limit their driving hours and who they can have in the car.  

But, let's be real, those temporary licenses are just a bandaid on a bullet hole. The real problem is that young drivers, as a group, just aren't ready for the responsibility, man. One psychologist dude, Marvin Zuckerman, even thinks 18 is too young to get a full license. He says young people, especially those under 20, just crave that adrenaline rush, you know? They love to push the limits.

So, maybe we should wait until that thrill-seeking fades a bit before handing them the keys. If we keep giving licenses to young teens, we're gonna see even more accidents, and the death toll is gonna be outta control.  

Think about it – in a few years, all those baby boomers' kids are gonna be old enough to drive, and it's gonna be a whole mess.

We need to get serious about this. Schools can still teach them about driving, but no one under 18 should be behind the wheel.  We can still have those temporary licenses and make them log some practice hours with a grown-up.

We need to make this a national thing, man. It's not like anyone's coming up with a new idea here. Just gotta make it happen.

So, I was  checking out some old Edison flicks at the Library of Congress, you know, the ones from way back in the day, like the 1890s and early 1900s.  There were a bunch of these  "trick films" -  they were all about pullin' the wool over your eyes with crazy editing. I spent a good while figuring out how they did their magic, how they made things appear and disappear, and what made some of those later films stand out from the crowd. 

Most of these early trick films were like little stages, all set up in front of a camera.  They never moved the camera around, just kept it fixed like you'd see in a play.  They stuck to long shots and the occasional medium shot, never getting up close and personal like we do today.  And get this - each trick was usually just one long shot, kinda like a continuous performance.

They really leaned into that stage vibe, just like vaudeville or magic shows.  The actors would walk side-to-side, never coming forward or backward towards the camera. It was like they were stuck in a box, ya know?  Take "Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel" for example, everyone just shuffled back and forth.

And because they didn't move close to the camera, they never used close-ups.  It was all about seeing the whole picture at once, just like in a live performance.

Because each trick was basically one long shot, the whole film was usually super short, maybe a minute or less.  Most of them were just a quick series of tricks, like magic, disappearing acts, or switching stuff around. It wasn't really about telling a story, more like a bunch of mini-acts strung together.  Oh, but here's the sneaky part - what looks like one shot to you might actually be a bunch of shots glued together to make the illusion work. Check out "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots" - it looks like one long shot, but if you look closer, you'll see where they secretly switched out Mary's head!

Alright, listen up! This guy John Taylor, real stickler for freedom, especially when it came to farming.  He was all about folks doing their own thing, no government meddling.  He thought farming was the best gig ever, and that's what shaped his whole take on how things should run.  He wanted a government that said "Hey, you do your thing, we'll do ours, and let's keep it that way."

He thought America had a clean slate, no old traditions getting in the way. That meant they could build a government that worked for everyone, based on the idea that everyone's got basic rights that no one can mess with.  He was big on those "natural rights" – like, if one gets squashed, they all get squashed, ya know?  No way the government should be messing with those.  

John thought the government should be like this cautious guardian, keeping the good stuff from getting messed up and stopping the bad stuff from going too far.  He believed folks are good at heart, but also kinda sneaky, always looking out for number one.  That's why he wanted a government that protected your stuff, helped farmers out, and kept things fair.

He was all about sticking to the Constitution, too. No fancy interpretations, just plain words.  He thought the government should be small and leave folks alone, but not so small that it couldn't keep things in line. He even thought the Declaration of Independence was more important 'cause it showed the states were in charge, not some big ol' national government.

Okay, so check it out. We had this whole tracker for people who were ditching their cars and trying out other ways to get around campus, right? Well, things were totally rad at first, but then BAM!  Around month three, the number of folks logging their trips dropped like a rock. Kinda bummed us out, to be honest.

See, winter hit our college town, and everyone's less likely to bike or walk when it's freezing. Plus, December is crazy busy with schoolwork and holiday stuff. Who can be bothered with logging their commute when they're stressed out? And then, boom, holidays hit, and everyone's gone!

Even after things calmed down in January, the log submissions didn't really pick up.  I guess sometimes projects just lose steam after the initial hype.  

So, we decided to throw a "Carpool Challenge Week" in March.  We gave out prizes like gift certificates to local shops and restaurants – you know, the usual stuff. It kinda worked, but it was kinda like trying to keep a goldfish swimming upstream.  We learned that keeping people engaged is a real challenge, especially with holidays and school breaks messing with the flow.

Another thing we learned is that people love their cars! It's like a cultural thing. So, we gotta come up with some seriously awesome incentives to get folks ditching their rides. You know, like a sweet new bike, a hybrid car, or even a killer electric car! Maybe that would have kept things exciting. 

Honestly, the prizes we had were cool at first, but maybe we should have upped the ante as the project went on. Imagine if we had announced a couple of bikes in December, then a whole hybrid car in January… I bet people would have been all over it!

Yo, lemme break down this ETF thing for ya.  It's like a basket of investments, kinda like a mutual fund, but you can buy and sell it on the stock market like a regular stock.  You get the good stuff from both worlds:  diversification like a fund, but you can play the game like a stockbroker, ya know?   Short selling, margin buying, all that jazz. Plus, ETFs usually cost way less than mutual funds.   

But hold up, there's a catch. You gotta pay a fee every time you buy or sell, just like with stocks. And don't get me wrong, there are tons of different ETFs out there, so you gotta do your homework and figure out which one's right for you.  

Now, let's talk about this IHF ETF. I'm gonna look at its top ten holdings, which make up a big chunk of the whole thing.  My buddy Gage's dad got a hold of this thing called "HULK" on DVD, but I already saw it in the theater.  Anyway, I wanna see if owning just these top ten stocks is better than owning the whole ETF.

Let's see if these stocks really hold up their end of the bargain.  I'm gonna compare their returns and risk (that's the "Beta" stuff) to the whole ETF.  

Turns out, owning just those top ten stocks could give you a bigger return and less risk!  But hey, maybe I'm wrong.  We gotta do some fancy math to make sure those differences are real, ya know?

So, I'm gonna check the "standard deviation" of each of those stocks to see how they shake out compared to the whole ETF.  That'll tell me if owning those ten stocks is really a better deal than the whole shebang.

Yo, lemme tell ya about this poem, "Dream-Land," by Edgar Allan Poe. It's one of his favorites, ya know? He uses this word "Thulé," twice in the poem, and it's a big deal. This word goes way back to Virgil, an old-school dude who wrote about an island way up north, where everyone thought the world ended. Virgil used it, for sure, but Poe was a big fan of German writers, especially this guy Goethe. Now, this Goethe dude wrote this epic poem called "Faust," and it's super famous.  One part of "Faust" has a poem called "The King of Thulé," and it's about this king who loses his wife and goes totally bonkers, drinking himself to death.

Some folks say Poe was basically copying Goethe's style, especially since they both talk about this gloomy place called Thulé.  Poe even uses it twice in his "Dream-Land," like bookends, ya know?  

Poe's "Dream-Land" is all about this dark, lonely place, with dead friends haunting him, and everything's gray and lifeless. Kinda like the king in Goethe's poem, he's lost his wife and his will to live. It's like Poe stepped right into Goethe's poem. 

Poe loved German stuff, and he was a big fan of Tennyson, who was also into Goethe. So, Poe probably knew about Goethe's work even if he didn't directly copy him.

So, picture this: there's this chick, Jennifer, right? She goes to D&D grocery store, steps on some applesauce, BAM! Takes a spill and hurts her back real bad. Now, she's sayin' the store manager, Martin, shoulda known better 'cause folks had been slipping on spills before. See, two employees told him about the applesauce mess, but he was busy eatin' dinner and said "Nah, not my problem." Half an hour later, BAM! Jennifer goes down.

Now, Jennifer's lawyer's sayin' Martin acted real shady. They're talkin' 'bout "punitive damages," which means extra money to punish the store for bein' jerks. 

They're sayin' Martin knew folks were slipping and didn't care.  They say he acted like a total jerk, like he wanted Jennifer to get hurt. 

The judge ain't gonna throw this case out just yet, 'cause Jennifer's got some points. She can say that Martin knew spills were a problem, and he didn't do nothin' about it. Even though it might not be as clear-cut as "Martin wanted Jennifer to fall,"  it's still a decent argument. 

It all started back in October of 2009. Rich Wayne, a D&D employee, told Martin about the applesauce spill. Martin was all, "Dude, I'm busy eatin', deal with it yourself."  Then, Mary J. Haddigan, another worker, tells him again, and Martin gives the same lazy answer.  Well, half an hour later, Jennifer slips and breaks her back.  And get this,  five people already fell and got hurt that year because of spills!  

So, now Jennifer's takin' D&D to court, wantin' money for her pain and suffering, plus some extra dough to punish them for bein' reckless.

Yo, lemme tell ya 'bout this Islam class I took like, four years back at CBC. We were always going back and forth about whether Islam was, like, a bad religion or not.  It's even more messed up now than back then, ya know? Since 9/11, the media went from all "Islam is bad!" to "Islam is awesome!" like, overnight. I mean, back in 2001, could ya even imagine a prez running with a name like Barack Obama, who's got a Muslim family history? 

This Muhammad dude's story really got me thinking. See, I thought he was all about forcing people to convert, conquering tribes and making 'em Muslim. But this book paints him as a martyr, misunderstood and humble.  It's like he's the good guy who just, ya know, spread the truth, and people came to him on their own. 

There's even some stuff that's kinda like Jesus' story, like when Muhammad, like, multiplied some mutton and milk for forty guys. It's all super shady, ya know? Like they're trying to make Muhammad look like some kind of miracle worker, to, like, steal Jesus' thunder.

And get this, they got all these stories about how people converted, but they're all secondhand.  It's like, "So-and-so heard from so-and-so who heard from..." It's all fishy, man.

The worst part is, they're trying to make Muhammad out to be this perfect, humble, wise dude. But history says different. Muhammad was a warrior, man!  I just wonder if Muslims today know the real deal about this guy.

Alright, lemme tell ya somethin' 'bout Christianity.  It's like this, Jesus had his own way of doin' things, ya know?  But then, after he was gone, things started to change. Kinda like when you leave a pizza out too long - it gets all weird and different. Christianity went on its own wild ride, gettin' further and further from Jesus' original message.

Now, these days, everyone's all about change, right?  They wanna try new things and break the rules.  But there are still some folks stuck in the old ways, clingin' to what they know. They ain't gonna let go easy.

But here's the thing: more and more people are gonna start lookin' back, seein' all the stuff that got added to Christianity over the years. They're gonna wanna know what Jesus really meant, what he truly taught.  It might take a while, maybe decades, maybe even centuries, but it's gonna happen.

Think of it like rewindin' a tape.  Christianity's gonna go back to its roots, strip away all the extra stuff, until it's just Jesus' pure teachings. People are gonna be like, "Hey, remember when things were simpler?"  And they'll start worshipin' like they did back in Jesus' time, just followin' his lead.

The church will still be around, leadin' the way, but everything's gonna be different.  All the different groups and denominations, they'll start to look more and more alike. It's like when the Roman Empire went from crushin' Christians to bein' ruled by 'em.

History's full of these big shifts, y'know? It's like a rollercoaster, goin' up and down, changin' direction. And this next big shift's gonna be all about Christianity, goin' back to its original form, gettin' rid of all the extra stuff, and bringin' everyone together. 

And get this, a big part of it's gonna be seein' Jesus' words in a new way, like metaphors, not just plain ol' instructions.  It's like, he was tryin' to tell us somethin' deeper, somethin' we gotta figure out on our own.

So what happened after Jesus? Well, way back when, there was just Judaism. That was the start of it all, ya know? One God, the Bible, that's what it was all about.  The Jews, they weren't all on the same page, though. They had their different groups, like the Sadducees, the Pharisees, the Essenes, and so on.

Alright, lemme tell ya somethin' about this book, *The Jungle*. It's a real eye-opener, man. It shows how humans, deep down, are kinda selfish, ya know? They're all about lookin' out for number one and makin' their lives better, but they don't care about anyone else, especially if that someone's lower on the food chain.

You see it everywhere in the book, especially with those factory owners and bosses. All they care about is makin' their companies bigger and richer, no matter what. They don't give a hoot about the people workin' for them or the damage they're doin' to the environment.

Sinclair, the guy who wrote it, paints a pretty grim picture. He describes these factories like giant, smokin' monsters, spewin' out pollution and stink.  He's sayin' these guys don't care about the people, the animals, nothin'!

And those bosses? Forget about it! They treat their workers like dirt.  They make 'em work long hours, then just fire 'em without a second thought. No help, no nothin'. It's like they're slaves, trapped in this system with no way out.  

There weren't many rules back then to protect people, so these guys could get away with anything.  They pushed their workers to the limit, made 'em work in awful conditions. It's messed up, man. They expected people to just take it, to die in those factories or whatever.

Even the unions weren't much help. They were more about makin' money off the workers than actually standin' up for 'em.

It's a tough story, but it shows a dark side of humanity. It makes you think about how we treat each other, how we let greed and power corrupt us.

Okay, so like, some writers, ya know, they use super cool tricks to make you feel a certain way about stuff. It's like, they're trying to plant a vibe. Fitzgerald, the dude who wrote *The Great Gatsby*, he's a master at this. He's like, 'Hey, let's pair up some random words, just to see what kinda crazy feeling it makes'. He also loves using symbols, like colors, to sneak in these extra meanings.  

Take colors, for example: gold, green, white, gray, even red and pink. Fitzgerald, he's got a whole system going on with these colors, and he uses them to give you a sneak peek into what's really important in the story.

White and gray, they're like his secret weapons. He uses white to show you something fancy and high class, like,  'Look at Daisy, she's always dripping in white!' But then there's gray, which is like the tired, old version of white. It's like, 'This is all so boring and predictable'. He throws these colors everywhere at the beginning of the book, like, everyone's wearing white, even Gatsby's parties are kinda whitewashed. You see, Fitzgerald, he's setting the stage, building up this whole vibe.

Then, there's all these little details, like, Nick going down "white chasms" or people's names being "gray" on a list. It's all about uniformity, like, everything is just the same, nothing special.

So, when Fitzgerald suddenly starts describing Daisy in white again, you get this feeling of, 'Oh, she's not really who she seems, she's just another pretty face in a sea of white'. And that's his point, man. He wants you to see how things aren't always what they seem, how even the prettiest things can be empty.

So, check it out, this place in San Diego County called Potrero is a total paradise for growing stuff. They got sunshine all year round, so they grow all kinds of awesome stuff like tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, even peppers! And get this, people are crazy for organic food here. They got these cool farms where you can join up and get fresh veggies straight from the source, but everyone's always on a waiting list! Organic eggs and milk are like, the hottest thing. Some of these farms are even super chill and let you take tours, go birdwatching, and hike around. It's like a win-win, ya know?  The government's got programs to help farmers who do this kinda stuff, so they can make some dough while helping out the environment. 

But here's the thing, organic farming ain't always easy. It takes a lot of elbow grease to keep those pesky bugs and weeds away without using chemicals. Plus, sometimes things don't grow as well as they do with regular farming. It's like, you gotta put in extra effort to make it work. 

Now, this one place in Potrero, it's 160 acres of chaparral, grasslands, and oak trees. It's right next to this huge forest called the Cleveland National Forest, and it's home to all sorts of cool critters, some of them endangered, like kangaroo rats, frogs, and even butterflies. It's been around forever, used by Native Americans first, then ranchers and wood sellers. 

I was checking out this website and found this farm nearby that's doing organic stuff. They're killing it! So, I figured this Potrero place could do the same thing.

Listen up, 'cause this is important stuff. When you're dealin' with folks from a different scene, ya gotta get their groove. Culture ain't just some big ol' label, it's like a whole way of life, ya know? Don't go thinkin' everyone from the same place is all the same, 'cause that's a surefire way to mess things up.  Like, sayin' all Russians are stubborn or all Japanese are easygoing, that's just plain wrong.

The real deal is to figure out what makes that culture tick, what's important to 'em, and how that'll play out when you're tryin' to make a deal.  When you're meetin' folks from a different background, you're gonna see things through your own lens, and that's natural. But don't let that cloud your judgment.

To understand 'em, you gotta dig deep. Learn about their history, their beliefs, their hang-ups. Don't go tryin' to change 'em, just accept 'em for who they are, especially if you're the underdog at the table. And remember, respect goes a long way.  If you show respect for their customs and beliefs, it'll make things a whole lot smoother.

Culture ain't just about countries either.  Even inside a company, there's a whole vibe goin' on.  Some places are all about long hours, others are laid-back. You can tell a lot by how folks dress, how they talk, how they get things done, even how they give back to the community. Just look at how different companies are here in America, from coast to coast, city to suburbs. It's wild how diverse things can be, even in one place.

Values are the real key, though. They're the heart of a culture, the "why" behind everything. If a culture values saving face or harmony, you ain't gonna see them embarrassin' their company or boss just to win a deal.  And a culture that's all about tough negotiations? They ain't gonna settle for the first thing that comes along.

So, before you even sit down at the table, do your homework. Figure out what makes 'em tick, what they value. But don't forget, a little personal touch goes a long way too. Get to know your opponent, show 'em you're more than just a business deal. That's how you make a real connection.

Okay, so these two brainiacs, Anselm and Aquinas, both think there's a Big Guy upstairs, ya know? And they both wanna prove it, like a weird game of one-upmanship. But since I'm way more down-to-earth, lemme break it down for ya.

Anselm, he's all about lookin' inside yourself, like, "Dude, God's already in your head, so you gotta believe!" Kinda like when you know your goldfish is hungry even before he starts tappin' on the glass. Anselm thinks faith is the key, no need for all that fancy proof stuff. 

Then there's Aquinas, the logic master. He's like, "Nah, man, I got five solid reasons why God's gotta be real!" He's talkin' 'bout change, cause and effect, stuff like that. Like, if you see a bunch of pieces of a puzzle, you just KNOW there's a missing one, right? Aquinas says it's the same with God - the universe makes sense 'cause there's gotta be a Big Guy behind it all.

So, who's got the better argument? Honestly, both of 'em make some pretty good points. But neither one's gonna convince me without a little more than just words, ya know? I need some solid evidence, not just head-scratchin' theories.

Yo, so like, way back in the day, like, super long ago, there was this dude named Buddha, right? He was a prince, but he was all, 'Nah, this royal life ain't for me.' So, he ditched it all and became enlightened. His teachings, they became this big thing called Buddhism. There's a bunch of different types of Buddhism, but the most hardcore one is called Theravada. It's like, over 2,500 years old, and things have changed a bit since Buddha was chillin'.

Take this festival they have in Sri Lanka, for example. They call it the water-cutting ceremony. Monks and regular folks participate, and it's kinda religious, but Buddha never talked about this kinda thing. It's just one example of how Buddhism has evolved over time. It's not just the goofy traditions, but even the deep, core beliefs have changed a little.

Why? Well, there are a bunch of reasons. Some stuff comes from inside the Buddhist community, like, changes made by monks and regular Buddhists. Other stuff comes from outside, like, people who aren't Buddhist. Sometimes these outside forces are cool, sometimes they're a total drag. 

Let's break down some key terms first, 'cause we're gonna use them a lot.  We got 'internal' and 'external' forces. Internal means stuff coming from Buddhists, whether they're monks or not. External means stuff from people outside Buddhism.  Then we have 'hostile' and 'benign'. Hostile forces mess with Buddhism, try to hurt it, or whatever. Benign forces don't really care about Buddhism, they just do their thing, which might accidentally help or hurt Buddhism.  

Alright, now let's get down to the basics of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists believe in the 'Triple Gem': Buddha, the teachings (Dhamma), and the community (Sangha). The Dhamma is basically the holy scriptures, like the Tripitaka.  There's the Sutta Pitaka (Buddha's words), the Vinaya Pitaka (rules for monks), and the Abhidhamma Pitaka (the deep, philosophical stuff). 

They talk about things like Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (suffering is real), and Anicca (everything's temporary).  You gotta get a handle on these ideas to break free from Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth.  When you do that, you also ditch all the bad stuff: lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). You become enlightened, like a boss.

The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for how to live. Regular folks have five precepts: don't kill, don't lie, don't steal, don't mess around sexually, and don't get wasted on drugs. Monks, they've got a whole lotta rules to follow. The most important idea in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths:

1. Life is suffering (Dukkha).
2. Suffering is caused by attachment.
3. Suffering can be overcome.
4. There's a path to overcome suffering (the Eightfold Path).

So, get this: America and Mexico, they were like, totally at odds for, like, forever! I'm talking 57 years, from 1836 to 1893! It was a real thing, man, like a super intense rivalry. Remember that time America went and smashed Mexico in that war back in 1846? Yeah, that was a big deal. America took Texas and all that Southwest land for itself. Boom! Total power move.  

But it wasn't just about land, ya know? They also butted heads over religion, culture, the whole shebang. Like, imagine being all different and then having to live next door to each other. It's a recipe for disaster, right? 

It's kinda like, you know, when your neighbor's dog keeps digging in your garden. You gotta be all "Hey, chill out, dude!" about it. Except instead of a dog, it's a whole country. 

Anyway, America and Mexico had their fair share of run-ins, like a whole bunch of them. They were like, "Nope, not gonna share!" over stuff like who should be in charge and what's considered cool.  And get this, an old dude named David M. Pletcher said that America's had way more drama with Mexico and Cuba than with any other country. Not cool, man.

Religion was a major sticking point too. Back then, America was all "We don't dig that Catholicism!" and Mexico was like, "Screw you, we're sticking with our faith!" It's kind of like the whole Cold War thing, but instead of Communism, it was Catholic-phobia. It's like they thought if you didn't believe the same thing, you were the enemy.

And guess what? It all stemmed from those old colonial times when England and Spain were at each other's throats.  They passed down all that bad blood to their kids, and America and Mexico just couldn't seem to get over it. 

They fought over borders, stole each other's stuff, and pulled all sorts of shady stuff. It was a mess, man! But eventually, Mexico realized they needed America for stuff, and America wanted to control their economy instead of just taking their land. So, the rivalry fizzled out, but it took a long time.

So, fifteen years back, BAM! I'm hit with this crazy illness out of nowhere. Never even heard of it before!  See, I was a nurse, figured it was the safe bet.  Everyone kept saying, "You'll always have a job, people get sick all the time!"  So I did it, even though my real dream was to be a scientist or maybe a journalist, or heck, both!  But here I was, 46, single, no cash in the bank, and totally outta commission.  Now, fifteen years and counting on disability, I've got nothin' left to call my own.  Scrapping by, that's the name of the game. Every day's a fight to keep my head above water, a constant battle for security, safety, and even just my self-respect.

Nothing's a sure thing anymore, but here's the deal: without my family and a few awesome friends, I wouldn't have made it this far. Believe me, when disaster hits, strong doesn't even begin to describe it. 

Life throws curveballs, big and small, all the time. No amount of planning can stop everything. Some stuff, you just can't handle alone.

We need to stop relying so much on the government, it's crumbling faster than a stale cookie. But I'd rather see folks helping each other out, building each other up, asking for help when they need it.  

Those Conservatives keep talking about how "rugged individualism" built this country, but back in the day, what got folks through tough times wasn't being tough, it was kindness, respect, and sharing what you had. Those pioneers crossing the Rockies? They didn't make it without lookin' out for each other.


So yeah, be prepared. I am. Got my disaster kit, first aid, water purifiers, plastic sheeting for the windows, the whole shebang. Flashlights, batteries, candles, matches... you name it, I got it.  If you've got the space and the means, a little farm and some canning supplies?  Go for it!  Wood stove, too, if you're not stuck in an apartment. 

But here's the kicker: get to know your neighbors.

Okay, so, like, why do critters evolve the way they do? Is there some kinda rulebook for evolution, ya know? Back in the day, this dude named D'Arcy Thompson said we're still figuring out how to talk about living things in numbers, and wouldn't ya know it, that's still kinda true. But, lately, folks have been using math to try and understand how shells grow, like, from baby to adult, and how that's changed over time. We're doing the same thing with these cool clams called Prunum. We're taking pictures of their shells, measuring all sorts of stuff, and then using computer programs to make up new shell shapes.  It's like, "What if a shell did this instead of that?" Kinda like when you play with LEGOs, but with science! We're also doing experiments to see how these different shapes actually work.

Think of a shell like a spiral staircase that goes all the way around. Each step is a whorl, and they all spin around a central column called the columella. Sometimes the steps get bigger, sometimes they stay the same, and there's a line separating each step, called a suture. Usually, the biggest step is the last one, called the body whorl. The rest of the steps are called the spire, and the very tip is called the apex. And there's a hole at the bottom called the aperture where the clam sticks its head out. 

You can look at a shell from different angles, like from the top, bottom, front, or back.

Counting the whorls is kinda like slicing a cake. You look at the top, find the first line, and then count how many slices there are. We even look at how the opening of the shell changes as it grows. Imagine tracing the path of the opening as the clam builds its shell, that's like a map of its growth! We can even use math to make that map and see what would happen if the clam grew differently. Kinda neat, huh?

Yo, lemme tell ya about Indonesia and their baby peeps.  For the last ten years, things haven't been changin' much when it comes to babies dyin' before they even turn one.  They're doin' alright with stuff like clean water and toilets, but when it comes to keepin' moms and babies healthy, they ain't quite makin' the cut.  

Turns out, they're gettin' better at havin' babies with helpers around, but not all helpers are created equal.  Some are just midwives, and they can't handle tough situations, ya know?  Like when a mama starts bleedin' too much after givin' birth, those midwives are outta their league.  So even though they're makin' progress, it's kinda fake news.  Also, fewer kids are seein' doctors for tummy aches and stuff.  And postnatal care? Forget about it, that's a mess too.

And here's the kicker:  cesarean sections are way too low, especially in the country parts.  In the city, they do 'em a decent amount, but in the sticks, not so much.  It's like the rich folks get all the good stuff.  

The poor folks are strugglin' to get care too, 'cause it costs too much.  

So what's the answer?  Should they focus on specific programs or fix the whole health system?   Programs are easier, they get results faster, but they can also mess things up.  Like, they might pour all their money into one thing, leaving other stuff to rot. Plus, ya get a bunch of programs doin' the same thing, but all disorganized.  Talk about a headache!

Alright, so Victorian books are all about fancy details and rich folks, right? But then there's these two, "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights," that kinda break the mold. They're Victorian, but they're like, "Nope, we're gonna throw in some mystery and weird stuff!"  It makes the characters way more interesting because we get a peek into their heads and what makes them tick.

Like, take this bit from "Oliver Twist":

"And now, hosts of bewildering and confusing ideas came crowding on his mind. He seemed to be still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily disputing: for the very words they said, sounded in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, … he found that he was talking to them…. Suddenly he started back at the report of fire arms; and there rose into the air loud cries and shouts; lights gleamed before his eyes, and all was noise and tumult, as some unseen hand bore him hurriedly away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which weared and tormented him incessantly.” 

(Dickens, 220)

See, in these stories, things get kinda dreamlike and mysterious, especially with Oliver. It's like a window into his mind, showing us what's hurting him and how he sees the crazy stuff going on around him.

When Oliver gets shot, it's like he's reliving it in a nightmare. He's overwhelmed, like he has no control, and everything feels numb. It's scary because it shows how broken he is and how much Fagin has messed with him. It makes you wonder who's really in charge of his fate.


In "Wuthering Heights," it's different, but the mystery is still there. It's more about the darkness and hidden secrets of the characters.

Okay, so picture this: a couple years back, I was helping out at this after-school program, you know, tutoring those little elementary schoolers. I was pretty good at English and reading, so that's what I mostly focused on.  Then this kid, Adrian, comes along. He was in like third or fourth grade, I think, and he was really struggling to read. It was weird, man. Some letters he'd nail, others? Not even close. It was like his brain was playing some kind of  letter-pronouncing game, and it hated him.  See, Adrian was Latino, and he spoke perfect English, which made it even weirder.  We were stuck in this reading rut until one day, Adrian's mom came in.  She didn't speak a lick of English, just Spanish.  My Spanish was like, "hola" and "gracias" level, but somehow we managed to chat.  BAM! It hit me like a ton of bricks. Adrian wasn't dumb, he just didn't know the English alphabet that well. It was like teaching someone to read using a completely different alphabet. I don't know if that helped him much in the long run, but I hope he's doing better now. 

Anyway, that's why I'm bringing this whole language barrier thing up. It's a big deal, especially here in California. It's not always as obvious as you think.  Even a kid who speaks English perfectly can still struggle with reading if they haven't got a good grasp of the alphabet. Everyone knows this is a problem, but what can we do about it? Adrian was kind of a simple case - some extra English reading help, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciation. But for kids who barely speak English, it's way more complicated.  There's no magic bullet.  Dual language programs, immersion, private tutors, ESL classes - none of it works alone.  We need to mix and match! 

First off, dual language programs are awesome, not just for kids whose first language is Spanish, but for everyone. Studies show they actually do better in school!  People are scared about this, saying it wastes resources and benefits only a few.  But that's wrong. Think about it - if this was the norm, not the exception, everyone would benefit!

So how do we do it?  Do we make all teachers bilingual? Nah, that's crazy.  But I think we can have bilingual helpers, tutors, whatever you call them.

From the time we're little munchkins, most folks are told there's somethin' bigger out there, somethin' way beyond our tiny brains. Some get sent to Sunday School, others to Temple, or maybe they just bug out on their own lookin' for answers.  A lotta us just go with whatever religion our parents gave us, but some wise guys, they say "Nah, there ain't nothin' but this here brain and this here world."  We might even change our minds a bunch, findin' new ways to think about things. No matter what, we're all on this quest to figure out who we are, through our own messed up, unique views on what's holy and what ain't. We're all searchin' for a light in the darkness, somethin' to guide us outta the shadows and into the sunshine.

"A cardinal," my old man said when I asked him what bird he liked best. We were sittin' on the porch, listenin' to the rain poundin' on the roof like a freakin' drum solo. Water was pourin' down the gutters, drownin' the plants by the steps.  He looked out at the rain, like he was half-searchin' for somethin', half-rememberin'. He'd gotten thinner, clothes hangin' off him like a bad Halloween costume.  His hair was gettin' thinner too, like a spooky, bald spot was comin' for him. He kept lookin' at the rain, wouldn't meet my eyes.  I felt lonely, scared, and couldn't bring myself to talk to him about how much I was gonna miss him.  Talkin' about it woulda made it real, and that was too much for both of us.  So I just hugged him, sat back down, scooted my chair closer, and joined him in watchin' the rain fall on that June night.

My dad kicked the bucket in December that year, five days after I turned twenty-two.  The chemo and radiation didn't make him feel any better, but it kept him around for a few months longer than the docs thought he'd last.  I couldn't say what good that did, though.  What kinda God does that?  Alone in the dark, I didn't pray.  If God was out there, I figured he stopped listenin' to me ages ago. 

I didn't wanna be there when he left this world for whatever came next.  So I wasn't.  Couldn't watch the man who made me fade away.  I wanted to remember him the way he lived, not the way he died. Besides, I knew my dad better than anyone else, better even than his own family.  I knew he wouldn't want me to be some sad spectator at his death. I curled up in bed for three days, waitin' for the news.

Nobody even called.

So, get this, people have been yapping about Gothic novels forever. Some say they're a total snoozefest, others think they're the bee's knees, ya know, all "terrible sublime" and stuff. This dude Ian Watt, real smart guy, says they're basically a "weird mix of old and new," which kinda makes sense when you think about it.

This whole thing started with this book, "The Castle of Otranto," by this fella Horace Walpole. He took all these old school, like, super dramatic theatre ideas and mixed them up with the newfangled way of writing novels back then – you know, where you get up close and personal with the characters' minds.  He calls it a "Gothic story," and BAM, the genre was born!

Gothic novels are like a throwback to the spooky, medieval vibes, with castles, knights, and all that jazz. But even back then, "Gothic" was kinda seen as old-fashioned and clunky compared to the "modern" stuff. 

But here's the kicker – even though Gothic is, like, ancient history, it still sticks around because it's got this cool combo of drama and mystery. It's like, both out of date and totally fresh at the same time, which is kinda mind-blowing.

One big theme in Gothic novels is this thing called chivalry. It's all about knights being brave, honorable, and totally awesome. Gothic writers loved it because they thought modern society was lacking that whole chivalrous vibe.  They used chivalry to make the "Gothic past" look super idealized and romantic, kinda like a sneak peek at the future of the Romantic era. 

Walpole, the dude who started it all, was writing during some seriously messed up times politically. He was worried sick about the future, and maybe he thought the good ol' days of chivalry were gone for good. In his book, he shows this through his character Frederic, who's basically a perfect knight in shining armor. 

He's a prince, he's been through some serious heartache, and he's supposed to be dead. It's like a dramatic, over-the-top version of a knight, which kinda sets the stage for the whole Gothic trope of going overboard.

Alright, lemme break down this whole "supply chain" thing for ya. It's basically how stuff gets from the "I want it!" stage all the way to your doorstep. Think of it like a big, crazy race with lots of different players. 

This guy named Keith Oliver, back in 1982, was the first to use the fancy term "supply chain management." He figured out that to make things run smooth and get stuff to folks fast, ya gotta plan ahead, make it happen, and keep an eye on everything. 

There are six main players in this supply chain game: making stuff, getting the stuff, keeping track of the stuff, deciding where stuff goes, moving stuff around, and sharing info about the stuff. Managers gotta juggle all these things to make sure customers are happy.

First off, you gotta make the stuff!  That's the "production" part. It's like the first step in a big recipe, where you figure out what to make, how much to make, where to make it, and who's gonna do it. Managers gotta know what people want, so they check out the market – that's like lookin' at what's hot and trendy. 

Once they know what folks want, they decide what to produce and how much. Then they gotta pick the best place to make it, making sure it's got everything it needs and can handle the workload. 

Next up is "supply," which is all about finding the best people and places to help make your stuff. Maybe ya got different parts of the production process spread out, or maybe ya wanna outsource some stuff to other companies. That's where "velocity" comes in – doin' things fast and cheap while still keeping quality high.

So, picture this, right?  Ellen Page, that chick from Juno, she's standing on a street corner, holding up this cardboard sign.  And get this, it says, "Hitler is alive in Burma!" Can you believe it?  Burma, which is also called Myanmar, is this weird country in Southeast Asia where these guys in charge, the military, they've been running things since 1962.  They're kinda like the bullies of the world, always making trouble and not letting anybody else have a say.  

Back in 2007, a bunch of monks, like the peaceful kind, they decided to stand up to these guys.  It started with these little protests, like, "Hey, we want a better life!" But the military, they got all scared and started beating people up.  They even went into the monk's temples and trashed the whole place. It got so bad that journalists who were just trying to do their job got thrown in jail.  One guy, Kenji, he was just taking pictures, and they killed him!  

This isn't new, though.  Governments have always been like that, trying to boss people around and keep all the power for themselves.  Like, remember those Roman emperors way back when?  They thought they were gods!  And then there's Japan, where the emperor is supposed to be a god too!  And don't even get me started on our president, George W. Bush. Duke Ellington, he was a real jazz legend, ya know?  He played piano, but he was even better at making music for his whole band. He knew how to write tunes that let each player shine, even if it was just a little solo. He was like a conductor, but he also knew how to make the whole orchestra sound like one big, crazy good instrument. 

Heck, he even used voices like instruments in some of his stuff. Like this song "Creole Love Call".  It's a slow blues song, and the singer, he's not singing words, he's just making sounds, like an instrument!  It's kinda cool.

This guy, he knew how to make each player sound their best, and he knew how to make them all sound good together. He wrote some of the coolest, most amazing jazz music ever!  He even used a trumpet guy named Bubber Miley and a singer named Baby Cox to do this thing where they were callin' and respondin' to each other. It was like they were making music with their voices and their horns at the same time.

Then there's this other song, "It Don't Mean a Thing".  Ellington had this trombone player, Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton. He was a regular in Ellington's band, and in this song, he plays the first note of the song on his trombone, and it's like, BAM! You know that's Ellington right away!

She'd always felt this hole inside, somethin' she couldn't quite put her finger on. This need, this want, that just wouldn't quit. It started when she was 14, hittin' that awkward teenage phase, and it was still there at 17.  Now, she knew it wasn't somethin' she could just buy, it was somethin' more... someone. But nobody, not a single dude, had ever caught her eye.  Some had tried, bless their hearts, makin' all those goofy moves, but nothin' clicked. She wracked her brain, tryin' to figure out what was up with her. Theories bounced around, but nothin' stuck. So, she just kept livin', always wonderin' what this itch was all about.

Home life was usually pretty chill. Her folks were cool cats, never fightin' and rarely even gettin' into it with her.  Arguments were mostly about her tryin' to spread her wings and show 'em who she was.  They were a calm bunch, but she brought the energy, the fun, the whole shebang. That, plus her sweet personality, made her a real hit wherever she went.


But today wasn't a chill day.  She was wanderin' around, lookin' for somethin' to spark her creativity, when she heard a yelp from the kitchen. It was her mom, and her voice sounded scared. She bolted in there, heart poundin', shoutin', "Mom! Mom, what's wrong?!" There she was, sprawled out on the floor, whimperin' in pain. "Ow... swe - ty, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital," she managed between breaths.  

Her daughter sprang into action, her mom's words urgent and scared. "Okay Mom, just tell me where to get ya," she said, already thinkin' about how she'd get her to the car.  Her mom pointed weakly, and her daughter, thankful for those self-defense classes, scooped her up and carried her to the car. 


The hospital was a whirlwind of smells - antiseptic, sickness, and a whole lotta fear. But her daughter was focused on one thing: her mom. She rushed her in, hollerin' for help.  Doctors and nurses swarmed around, wheelin' her mom away for treatment, leavin' her daughter sittin' on a bench, worry gnawin' at her.


Turns out, her mom had fallen off a step stool reachin' for a vase on a high shelf.

Alright, so picture this: there's this super healthy way of eating called the "Mediterranean Diet," but lemme tell ya, it's a bit much for some folks. So, they came up with a simpler version called the 'alternate Mediterranean diet,' (or aMed for short). Basically, it's all about munching on plants like fruits, veggies, nuts, and beans, while keeping the meat and fatty stuff to a minimum. It's like, "Hey, let's load up on good stuff and ditch the bad!" 

Everyone knows that eating healthy is good for ya, right? Well, some earlier studies showed that folks who followed the Mediterranean Diet had less heart trouble and lived longer. This new study wanted to see if the aMed diet had the same effect, especially when it came to strokes. They followed a bunch of nurses for 20 years, asking 'em about what they ate every few years. And guess what? The nurses who ate the most like their Mediterranean diet buddies had a lower chance of getting heart disease and strokes!  They kept track of everything, like smoking, exercise, and even how many vitamins they popped. It's all about being super careful, ya know?

So, the study found that the more plants you eat and the less junk you stuff your face with, the less likely you are to have a heart attack or stroke.  Pretty simple, right?

Back in 2007, things got REAL hairy in America. People were losing jobs faster than you can say "sub-prime mortgage," and houses were going for less than a used pizza cutter.  The big money guys, the ones with names like Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers, they were singing the blues. See, they'd been handing out loans like candy to folks who couldn't really afford 'em –  like giving a goldfish a credit card!  And then, BAM! Those loans went south faster than a fry cook on vacation.  

It all started way back in the Clinton days, when everyone was feelin' good and the economy was hummin'. The Prez wanted another term, so they loosened up the rules on loans, thinking it'd make everyone happy. But, it was like lettin' loose a pack of rabid squirrels in a china shop.  

Some smart guy over at the New York Times, Steven Holmes, saw what was comin' a mile away. He's like, "Yo, this is gonna blow up!" But nobody listened.  

Then came those fancy new mortgage things, like adjustable-rate mortgages and mortgage-backed securities. They sound complicated, right? That's 'cause they are!  It was like weaving a giant, tangled mess of financial threads, and when one thread snapped, the whole thing started unravelin'.

And unravel it did. The housing bubble popped, and all those fancy investment banks were left holdin' the bag. They were in deep doo-doo, like a raccoon in a garbage can. Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers?  Gone. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac? Government bailouts, baby!  

So, there you have it. A bunch of bad decisions, a whole lotta greed, and a dash of economic ignorance led to a real mess.

Okay, so you wanna tell a story, right?  It's like showing off your best moves, painting a picture with words, making your readers go "Wow!"  Except, sometimes, you end up droning on and on, like a broken record.  That's exposition, and it's the writer's kryptonite.

See, we've all heard "Show, don't tell," but sometimes even the best writers get tripped up.  They get caught up in explaining *everything*, turning their story into a boring history lesson.  It's like that friend who always has to tell you *every single detail* about their day, even the boring parts.

Exposition is like that friend, except it's your story, and you're the one making everyone yawn.  In movies, it's when a character starts dumping information on another, like they're reading a Wikipedia article aloud.  In books, it's when the author does the same thing.

Think about it this way: you're reading a story, and suddenly you're told the heroine met her soulmate, got married in a huge fancy ceremony, and then BAM! He's murdered right in front of her.  Do you really want to spend two pages reading about it, with only a couple lines of dialogue for each character?

No way!  You want to *feel* the love they shared, see it in their actions and words, understand why his death is so devastating.  You want to see the heroine's grief, her strength, her vulnerability.  

It's all about adding depth, making the story come alive.  Instead of just telling us about the husband, let us *experience* him.  Show us his personality, his humor, his flaws.

Don't just tell us the characters met, got married, and he died.  Give us the story behind those events.  Make it real. Make it emotional. Make it unforgettable.

So, there's this thing about brothers, ya know? It's like, this super strong connection, like nothin' else.  It's got all these crazy feelings mixed up in it - love, pride, jealousy, even anger sometimes.  Brothers get each other, like, *deeply*. They see themselves in their brother, more than anyone else. But sometimes, when things go south, real bad, that bond shows its true colors, good or bad.  And that stuff, those feelings, they can really mess you up.  You gotta deal with the consequences, ya know? 'Cause when you look your brother straight in the eye and see yourself lookin' back, you see the real you, not how people think you are. It's in your actions, what you do, that shows what you're really made of.

This story, "The Scarlet Ibis",  it's all about that brother stuff.  These two guys, they got this intense connection, but it's messed up, kinda.  They're in this place, all beautiful and green, and they're on this crazy trip that ain't gonna end well.  There's this big fight, pride and disappointment clashing, and only one of 'em makes it out alive.

The story uses these brothers, Doodle and the narrator, to show how messed up this whole thing can get. The narrator, he's all about pride, from the start. He wants a brother who can keep up with him, someone who can do all the cool stuff he wants to do. Doodle, though, he's different. He's weak, can barely walk, and he's doomed from the start. The narrator's dreams, they get crushed.  He even thinks about killing Doodle, can you believe that? But then Doodle smiles at him, and... well, that changes things. It shows that deep down, he loves his brother, even if he's a pain in the neck sometimes.

Yo, check it! This brain thing is wild, right? Back in the day, folks thought it was like a wax tablet, then papyrus, then a book, and now they're sayin' it's like a computer. But hold up! Don't get too caught up in these comparisons, 'cause they don't tell the whole story. 

See, this brain of yours, it's like a total info-processing machine. It grabs stuff from your senses – touch, sound, sight – and turns it into electrical signals. Then it's like a crazy remix, all these signals bouncing around, getting analyzed from different angles. It's called bottom-up and top-down processing. Imagine you see a black box on a white background. Bottom-up is like figuring out the basics: "Hey, there's a shape, it's black, it's on a white thing." Top-down is like using your brainpower to go, "Aha! It's a box!"

But here's the kicker: your brain's got this filter, like a bouncer at a club, deciding what's important and what gets tossed aside. You see tons of grass when you look down, but your brain's like, "Nah, not worth remembering." But if someone shouts your name in a crowd, bam! It's front and center. So it's all about prioritizing, yo!

And speaking of remembering, your brain's got different storage compartments: sensory, working, and long-term. It's like filing cabinets, each with its own purpose. Sensory memory is fleeting, like a passing thought. Working memory holds stuff for a short while, like remembering a phone number. Long-term memory is the big vault, where all your experiences and knowledge chill. 

But how's all this knowledge organized? That's a big mystery. Some say it's like a network, with ideas connected like branches on a tree. Others think it's more like a giant puzzle, with pieces fitting together in complex ways. 

It's a wild ride, this brain thing, but it's what makes us, well, us.

Yo, check it! This book, "Brave New World," by Huxley, is totally dissing technology and the whole capitalist system. It's set up like a messed-up future where everyone's all about being part of the group and chasing instant happiness. They're basically puppets, man, dancing to the tune of the World Controller. This dude's got all the power, and he's running the show.

This book's got some deep stuff going on, like this Marxist thing. You know, it talks about how society's rigged, how everyone's the same, man, and how the rich guys are totally screwing over the poor folks. It's like Huxley saw the future and was like, "Whoa, this is messed up!"

He's using this thing called "false consciousness," which basically means the people are so busy chasing stuff they don't even realize they're being manipulated. They're all about buying stuff and getting their kicks, but they don't see the big picture. It's like they're brainwashed! The World Controller's like the ultimate puppet master, controlling everything from the get-go.

And it's not just about money, man. It's about power. The rich guys are on top, and they keep the poor guys down. It's a total power trip.

But here's the kicker: the people in this book, they don't even care! They're so used to being controlled that they don't even question it. They're like, "Yeah, this is how it's supposed to be." It's freakin' scary, man.

They don't have real relationships or feelings. They're all just shallow and superficial. It's like Huxley's saying that technology and capitalism are killing our humanity. We're becoming robots, man, just like the ones in that crazy future!

Yo, lemme tell ya 'bout this campus, man. I've been here for like, two and a half years, which is, like, four and a half semesters in their weird college speak. Getting around this place is a total drag, lemme tell ya. My first year I was stuck in these East Halls dorms, way out on the edge of campus, like, you could practically see the stadium from there.  Getting to class, especially to those places like Willard, which is like, in the middle of everything, was a freakin' marathon, especially when the weather decided to act up, which, let's be real, is, like, all the time here in State College. 

So, I was chatting with this old grad, not much older than me, and he told me that back in the day, East Halls was like, totally isolated. There was, like, this massive wasteland between it and the rest of the campus. Now, it's all filled up with sports fields, new buildings, and apartments. It's like they just keep expanding this place, making it even harder to get from point A to point B.

What's the answer to this mobility mess? Bikes, man!  Bikes are the way to go. But it's not just about having the bike; the campus needs to be built for bikers. This friend of mine, he got back into biking after, like, a long break, and he was all, "Dude, why did I ever stop?" He was like, "Bikes are the only way to get around." 

Besides being good for your bod, bikes are the most efficient way to travel.  A bowl of oatmeal and some pedaling and you're good for, like, 30 miles.

Now, I live off campus, just as far out as some dorms.  The smartest move I made this year? Buying a bike. My classes are in Thomas building, which is, like, a 25-minute walk from my place. On a bike? Five minutes, tops, if I push it.  The only problem? Pollock Road, the quickest way to Thomas, is, like, a pain in the butt, whether you're on a bike or walking. 

Walking's cool too, but I'm too busy for that. Without my bike, walking would be my only option, and that's, like, a whole other story. Walking to Thomas every day would add, like, 30-40 minutes to my day. That's, like, two and a half hours a week! And that's just Thomas. Add everything else, all the other classes, appointments, and stuff, and that's way too much time wasted.
